DNS:
dns domain name system is like a heirarchial system to help locate a particular ip
web broswer has something called local cache if the user often visits for example google.com it connects direct if not
the dns kicks in,
the broswer connects with the recursive resolver (ill call rr) rr will ask the rootserver
rootserver doesnt exactly know that ip of google.com but it know where to divert all the .com domains so it diverts rr to tdl top level domain each tdl has a list of subdomains they need to take care off for example .org .com or .edu
this tdl will ask the rr to check the authoritative domain name server 
where we can exactly find the domain resolution of the google
and then brswer will communicated by the isp or rr the google ip and connection is established 
and http resquest will send to load the google homepage
            Root Nameservers (13 worldwide)
                            ↓
            TLD Nameservers (.com, .org, .edu, etc.)
                            ↓
            Authoritative Nameservers (for specific domains)
                            ↓
            Recursive Resolvers (your ISP, 8.8.8.8, 1.1.1.1)
                            ↓
                    Your Device

